n","1315":"1315","Abt 1250":"circa 1250","1259":"1259","1273":"1273","1250":"1250","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England"},"en":{"Abt 1250–":"about 1250–Deceased","1273–Male":"1273–Deceased","1250–Male":"1250–Deceased","1315":"1315","Abt 1250":"about 1250","1259":"1259","1273":"1273","1250":"1250","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cowley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Cowley. One in Gloucestershire is named with Old English <i>cū</i> ‘cow’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’; two in Derbyshire have Old English <i>col</i> ‘(char)coal’ as the first element; and one near London is from Old English <i>cofa</i> ‘shelter, bay’ (see   Cove  ) or the personal name <i>Cofa</i>. The largest group, however, with examples in Buckinghamshire, Devon, Oxfordshire, and Staffordshire, were apparently named as ‘the wood or clearing of <i>Cufa</i>’; however, in view of the number of places called with this element, it is possible that it conceals a topographic term as well as a personal name.","Irish: shortened form of <b>Macaulay</b> (see   McCauley  ).","Manx: shortened form of Gaelic <i>Mac Amhlaoibh</i> ‘son of <i>Amhlaoibh</i>’ (a Gaelicized form of Old Norse <i>Óláfr</i>). For an alternative Manx form of the same patronymic see   Callow  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Coley","meanings":["English (Midlands): nickname for a swarthy person, from Middle English <i>coly</i> ‘coaly, coal-black’. The original short vowel is retained in the 16th century <i>colly</i> ‘dirtied with coal and soot’. Alternatively, a variant of   Cowley  .","Probably an Americanized form of Swiss German   Kohli   or   Kohler  ."]},{"name":"Cove","meanings":["English:","habitational name from a place called (the) Cove, examples of which are found in Hampshire, Wilts (a minor name in Leigh), Devon, and Suffolk, all from Old English <i>cofa</i>, which is recorded in literary sources with the sense ‘enclosed chamber’ but in placenames probably with extended senses such as ‘shelter, hut, building’, ‘hollow’ (in the case of the Devon name), and ‘creek, inlet’ (in the case of the Suffolk name).","nickname from Middle English <i>cof</i>, <i>cove</i> ‘eager, bold, courageous’ (Old English <i>cāf</i>)."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":9,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705190,"age":40,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705191,"age":65,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"Robert Cowley was born about 1250, in England. He had at least 1 son."},"et":{"Abt 1250–":"umbes 1250–Surnud","1273–Male":"1273–Surnud","1250–Male":"1250–Surnud","1315":"1315","Abt 1250":"umbes 1250","1259":"1259","1273":"1273","1250":"1250","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England"},"fi":{"Abt 1250–":"noin 1250–Kuollut","1273–Male":"1273–Kuollut","1250–Male":"1250–Kuollut","1315":"1315","Abt 1250":"noin 1250","1259":"1259","1273":"1273","1250":"1250","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England"},"fr":{"Abt 1250–":"environ 1250–Décédé","1273–Male":"1273–Décédé","1250–Male":"1250–Décédé","1315":"1315","Abt 1250":"environ 1250","1259":"1259","1273":"1273","1250":"1250","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Robert Cowley est né environ 1250, à Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fils."},"de":{"Abt 1250–":"um 1250–Verstorben","1273–Male":"1273–Verstorben","1250–Male":"1250–Verstorben","1315":"1315","Abt 1250":"um 1250","1259":"1259","1273":"1273","1250":"1250","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England","lifeSummary":"Robert Cowley wurde um 1250 in England geboren. Er hatte mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"Abt 1250–":"about 1250–Desede","1273–Male":"1273–Desede","1250–Male":"1250–Desede","1315":"1315","Abt 1250":"about 1250","1259":"1259","1273":"1273","1250":"1250","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England"},"hu":{"Abt 1250–":"1250 körül–elhunyt","1273–Male":"1273–elhunyt","1250–Male":"1250–elhunyt","1315":"1315","Abt 1250":"1250 körül","1259":"1259","1273":"1273","1250":"1250","1317":"1317","1290":"1290","England":"England"},"id":{"Abt 1250–":